<doc id="45241" wikidata="Q1065966" url="?curid=45241" title="Isomorphism theorems">
<text>In mathematics, specifically abstract algebra, the isomorphism theorems (also known as Noether&#x27;s isomorphism theorems) are theorems that describe the relationship among quotients, homomorphisms, and subobjects. Versions of the theorems exist for groups, rings, vector spaces, modules, Lie algebras, and other algebraic structures. In universal algebra, the isomorphism theorems can be generalized to the context of algebras and congruences.

== History ==
The isomorphism theorems were formulated in some generality for homomorphisms of modules by Emmy Noether in her paper &quot;Abstrakter Aufbau der Idealtheorie in algebraischen Zahl- und Funktionenkörpern&quot;, which was published in 1927 in Mathematische Annalen. Less general versions of these theorems can be found in work of Richard Dedekind and previous papers by Noether.

Three years later, B.L. van der Waerden published his influential &quot;Moderne Algebra&quot;, the first abstract algebra textbook that took the groups-rings-fields approach to the subject. Van der Waerden credited lectures by Noether on group theory and Emil Artin on algebra, as well as a seminar conducted by Artin, Wilhelm Blaschke, Otto Schreier, and van der Waerden himself on ideals as the main references. The three isomorphism theorems, called &quot;homomorphism theorem&quot;, and &quot;two laws of isomorphism&quot; when applied to groups, appear explicitly.

== Groups ==
We first present the isomorphism theorems of the groups.

===Theorem A (groups)===


Let &quot;G&quot; and &quot;H&quot; be groups, and let &quot;f&quot; : &quot;G&quot; → &quot;H&quot; be a homomorphism. Then:
# The kernel of &quot;f&quot; is a normal subgroup of &quot;G&quot;,
# The image of &quot;f&quot; is a subgroup of &quot;H&quot;, and
# The image of &quot;f&quot; is isomorphic to the quotient group &quot;G&quot; / ker(&quot;f&quot;).
In particular, if &quot;f&quot; is surjective then &quot;H&quot; is isomorphic to &quot;G&quot; / ker(&quot;f&quot;).

This theorem is usually called the &quot;first isomorphism theorem&quot;.

===Theorem B (groups)===

Let formula_1 be a group. Let formula_2 be a subgroup of formula_1, and let formula_4 be a normal subgroup of formula_1. Then the following hold:
# The product formula_6 is a subgroup of formula_1,
# The subgroup formula_4 is a normal subgroup of formula_6,
# The intersection formula_10 is a normal subgroup of formula_2, and
# The quotient groups formula_12 and formula_13 are isomorphic.
Technically, it is not necessary for formula_4 to be a normal subgroup, as long as formula_2 is a subgroup of the normalizer of formula_4 in formula_1. In this case, formula_4 is not a normal subgroup of formula_1, but formula_4 is still a normal subgroup of the product formula_6.

This theorem is sometimes called the &quot;second isomorphism theorem&quot;, &quot;diamond theorem&quot; or the &quot;parallelogram theorem&quot;.

An application of the second isomorphism theorem identifies projective linear groups: for example, the group on the complex projective line starts with setting formula_22, the group of invertible 2 × 2 complex matrices, formula_23, the subgroup of determinant 1 matrices, and formula_4 the normal subgroup of scalar matrices formula_25, we have formula_26, where formula_27 is the identity matrix, and formula_28. Then the second isomorphism theorem states that:

: formula_29

===Theorem C (groups)===
Let formula_1 be a group, and formula_4 a normal subgroup of formula_1.
Then
# If formula_33 is a subgroup of formula_1 such that formula_35, then formula_36 has a subgroup isomorphic to formula_37.
# Every subgroup of formula_36 is of the form formula_37 for some subgroup formula_33 of formula_1 such that formula_35.
# If formula_33 is a normal subgroup of formula_1 such that formula_35, then formula_36 has a normal subgroup isomorphic to formula_37.
# Every normal subgroup of formula_36 is of the form formula_37 for some normal subgroup formula_33 of formula_1 such that formula_35.
# If formula_33 is a normal subgroup of formula_1 such that formula_35, then the quotient group formula_56 is isomorphic to formula_57.

The last statement is sometimes referred to as the &quot;third isomorphism theorem&quot;. The first four statements are often subsumed under Theorem D below, and referred to as the &quot;lattice theorem&quot;, &quot;correspondence theorem&quot;, or &quot;fourth isomorphism theorem&quot;.

===Theorem D (groups)===
Let formula_1 be a group, and formula_4 a normal subgroup of formula_1.
The canonical projection homomorphism formula_61 defines a bijective correspondence
between the set of subgroups of formula_1 containing formula_4 and the set of (all) subgroups of formula_36. Under this correspondence normal subgroups correspond to normal subgroups. 

This theorem is sometimes called the &quot;correspondence theorem&quot;, the &quot;lattice theorem&quot;, and the &quot;fourth isomorphism theorem&quot;.

The Zassenhaus lemma (also known as the butterfly lemma) is sometimes called the fourth isomorphism theorem.

=== Discussion ===

The first isomorphism theorem can be expressed in category theoretical language by saying that the category of groups is (normal epi, mono)-factorizable; in other words, the normal epimorphisms and the monomorphisms form a factorization system for the category. This is captured in the commutative diagram in the margin, which shows the objects and morphisms whose existence can be deduced from the morphism formula_65. The diagram shows that every morphism in the category of groups has a kernel in the category theoretical sense; the arbitrary morphism &quot;f&quot; factors into formula_66, where &quot;ι&quot; is a monomorphism and &quot;π&quot; is an epimorphism (in a conormal category, all epimorphisms are normal). This is represented in the diagram by an object formula_67 and a monomorphism formula_68 (kernels are always monomorphisms), which complete the short exact sequence running from the lower left to the upper right of the diagram. The use of the exact sequence convention saves us from having to draw the zero morphisms from formula_67 to formula_70 and formula_71.

If the sequence is right split (i.e., there is a morphism &quot;σ&quot; that maps formula_72 to a -preimage of itself), then &quot;G&quot; is the semidirect product of the normal subgroup formula_73 and the subgroup formula_74. If it is left split (i.e., there exists some formula_75 such that formula_76), then it must also be right split, and formula_77 is a direct product decomposition of &quot;G&quot;. In general, the existence of a right split does not imply the existence of a left split; but in an abelian category (such as that of abelian groups), left splits and right splits are equivalent by the splitting lemma, and a right split is sufficient to produce a direct sum decomposition formula_78. In an abelian category, all monomorphisms are also normal, and the diagram may be extended by a second short exact sequence formula_79.

In the second isomorphism theorem, the product &quot;SN&quot; is the join of &quot;S&quot; and &quot;N&quot; in the lattice of subgroups of &quot;G&quot;, while the intersection &quot;S&quot; ∩ &quot;N&quot; is the meet.

The third isomorphism theorem is generalized by the nine lemma to abelian categories and more general maps between objects.

=== Note on numbers and names ===
Below we present four theorems, labelled A, B, C and D. They are often numbered as &quot;First isomorphism theorem&quot;, &quot;Second...&quot; and so on; however, there is no universal agreement on the numbering. Here we give some examples of the group isomorphism theorems in the literature. Notice that these theorems have analogs for rings and modules.


It is less common to include the Theorem D, usually known as the &quot;lattice theorem&quot; or the &quot;correspondence theorem&quot;, as one of isomorphism theorems, but when included, it is the last one.

== Rings ==
The statements of the theorems for rings are similar, with the notion of a normal subgroup replaced by the notion of an ideal.

=== Theorem A (rings) ===
Let formula_80 and formula_2 be rings, and let formula_82 be a ring homomorphism. Then:
# The kernel of formula_83 is an ideal of formula_80,
# The image of formula_83 is a subring of formula_2, and
# The image of formula_83 is isomorphic to the quotient ring formula_88.
In particular, if formula_83 is surjective then formula_2 is isomorphic to formula_88.

=== Theorem B (rings) ===
Let &quot;R&quot; be a ring. Let &quot;S&quot; be a subring of &quot;R&quot;, and let &quot;I&quot; be an ideal of &quot;R&quot;. Then:
# The sum &quot;S&quot; + &quot;I&quot; = {&quot;s&quot; + &quot;i&quot; | &quot;s&quot; ∈ &quot;S&quot;, &quot;i&quot; ∈ &quot;I&quot; } is a subring of &quot;R&quot;,
# The intersection &quot;S&quot; ∩ &quot;I&quot; is an ideal of &quot;S&quot;, and
# The quotient rings (&quot;S&quot; + &quot;I&quot;) / &quot;I&quot; and &quot;S&quot; / (&quot;S&quot; ∩ &quot;I&quot;) are isomorphic.

=== Theorem C (rings)===
Let &quot;R&quot; be a ring, and &quot;I&quot; an ideal of &quot;R&quot;. Then
# If formula_92 is a subring of formula_80 such that formula_94, then formula_95 is a subring of formula_96.
# Every subring of formula_96 is of the form formula_95 for some subring formula_92 of formula_80 such that formula_94.
# If formula_102 is an ideal of formula_80 such that formula_104, then formula_105 is an ideal of formula_96.
# Every ideal of formula_96 is of the form formula_105 for some ideal formula_102 of formula_80 such that formula_104.
# If formula_102 is an ideal of formula_80 such that formula_104, then the quotient ring formula_115 is isomorphic to formula_116.

=== Theorem D (rings)===
Let formula_27 be an ideal of formula_80. The correspondence formula_119 is an inclusion-preserving bijection between the set of subrings formula_92 of formula_80 that contain formula_27 and the set of subrings of formula_96. Furthermore, formula_92 (a subring containing formula_27) is an ideal of formula_80 if and only if formula_95 is an ideal of formula_96.

== Modules ==
The statements of the isomorphism theorems for modules are particularly simple, since it is possible to form a quotient module from any submodule. The isomorphism theorems for vector spaces (modules over a field) and abelian groups (modules over formula_129) are special cases of these. For finite-dimensional vector spaces, all of these theorems follow from the rank–nullity theorem.

In the following, &quot;module&quot; will mean &quot;&quot;R&quot;-module&quot; for some fixed ring &quot;R&quot;.

=== Theorem A (modules) ===
Let &quot;M&quot; and &quot;N&quot; be modules, and let &quot;φ&quot; : &quot;M&quot; → &quot;N&quot; be a module homomorphism. Then:
# The kernel of &quot;φ&quot; is a submodule of &quot;M&quot;,
# The image of &quot;φ&quot; is a submodule of &quot;N&quot;, and
# The image of &quot;φ&quot; is isomorphic to the quotient module &quot;M&quot; / ker(&quot;φ&quot;).
In particular, if &quot;φ&quot; is surjective then &quot;N&quot; is isomorphic to &quot;M&quot; / ker(&quot;φ&quot;).

===Theorem B (modules)===
Let &quot;M&quot; be a module, and let &quot;S&quot; and &quot;T&quot; be submodules of &quot;M&quot;. Then:
# The sum &quot;S&quot; + &quot;T&quot; = {&quot;s&quot; + &quot;t&quot; | &quot;s&quot; ∈ &quot;S&quot;, &quot;t&quot; ∈ &quot;T&quot;} is a submodule of &quot;M&quot;,
# The intersection &quot;S&quot; ∩ &quot;T&quot; is a submodule of &quot;M&quot;, and
# The quotient modules (&quot;S&quot; + &quot;T&quot;) / &quot;T&quot; and &quot;S&quot; / (&quot;S&quot; ∩ &quot;T&quot;) are isomorphic.

===Theorem C (modules) ===
Let &quot;M&quot; be a module, &quot;T&quot; a submodule of &quot;M&quot;.

# If formula_2 is a submodule of formula_131 such that formula_132, then formula_133 is a submodule of formula_134.
# Every submodule of formula_134 is of the form formula_133 for some submodule formula_2 of formula_131 such that formula_132.
# If formula_2 is a submodule of formula_131 such that formula_132, then the quotient module formula_143 is isomorphic to formula_144.
===Theorem D (modules)===
Let formula_131 be a module, formula_4 a submodule of formula_131. There is a bijection between the submodules of formula_131 that contain formula_4 and the submodules of formula_150. The correspondence is given by formula_151 for all formula_152. This correspondence commutes with the processes of taking sums and intersections (i.e., is a lattice isomorphism between the lattice of submodules of formula_150 and the lattice of submodules of formula_131 that contain formula_4).

== Universal algebra ==
To generalise this to universal algebra, normal subgroups need to be replaced by congruence relations.

A congruence on an algebra formula_92 is an equivalence relation formula_157 that forms a subalgebra of formula_158 considered as an algebra with componentwise operations. One can make the set of equivalence classes formula_159 into an algebra of the same type by defining the operations via representatives; this will be well-defined since formula_160 is a subalgebra of formula_158. The resulting structure is the quotient algebra.

=== Theorem A (universal algebra)===
Let formula_162 be an algebra homomorphism. Then the image of formula_163 is a subalgebra of formula_164, the relation given by formula_165 (i.e. the kernel of formula_163) is a congruence on formula_92, and the algebras formula_159 and formula_169 are isomorphic. (Note that in the case of a group, formula_170 iff formula_171, so one recovers the notion of kernel used in group theory in this case.)

=== Theorem B (universal algebra)===
Given an algebra formula_92, a subalgebra formula_164 of formula_92, and a congruence formula_160 on formula_92, let formula_177 be the trace of formula_160 in formula_164 and formula_180 the collection of equivalence classes that intersect formula_164. Then
# formula_182 is a congruence on formula_164,
# formula_184 is a subalgebra of formula_159, and
# the algebra formula_186 is isomorphic to the algebra formula_187.

=== Theorem C (universal algebra) ===
Let formula_92 be an algebra and formula_189 two congruence relations on formula_92 such that formula_191. Then formula_192 is a congruence on formula_193, and formula_159 is isomorphic to formula_195

=== Theorem D (universal algebra) ===
Let formula_92 be an algebra and denote formula_197 the set of all congruences on formula_92. The set
formula_197 is a complete lattice ordered by inclusion.
If formula_200 is a congruence and we denote by formula_201 the set of all congruences that contain formula_160 (i.e. formula_203 is a principal filter in formula_197, moreover it is a sublattice), then
the map formula_205 is a lattice isomorphism.

