<doc id="45265" wikidata="Q2248459" url="?curid=45265" title="De Bruijn–Newman constant">
<text>The de Bruijn–Newman constant, denoted by formula_1 and named after Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn and Charles Michael Newman, is a mathematical constant defined via the zeros of a certain function formula_2, where formula_3 is a real parameter and formula_4 is a complex variable. More precisely,
:formula_5,
where formula_6 is the super-exponentially decaying function
:formula_7
and formula_1 is the unique real number with the property that formula_9 has only real zeros if and only if formula_10.

The constant is closely connected with Riemann hypothesis. Indeed, the Riemann hypothesis is equivalent to the conjecture that formula_11. Brad Rodgers and Terence Tao proved that formula_12, so the Riemann hypothesis is equivalent to formula_13. A simplified proof of the Rodgers–Tao result was later given by Alexander Dobner.

== History ==
De Bruijn showed in 1950 that formula_9 has only real zeros if formula_15, and moreover, that if formula_9 has only real zeros for some formula_3, formula_9 also has only real zeros if formula_3 is replaced by any larger value. Newman proved in 1976 the existence of a constant formula_1 for which the &quot;if and only if&quot; claim holds; and this then implies that formula_1 is unique. Newman also conjectured that formula_12, which was proven forty years later, by Brad Rodgers and Terence Tao in 2018.

== Upper bounds ==
De Bruijn&#x27;s upper bound of formula_23 was not improved until 2008, when Ki, Kim and Lee proved formula_24, making the inequality strict.

In December 2018, the 15th Polymath project improved the bound to formula_25. A manuscript of the Polymath work was submitted to arXiv in late April 2019, and was published in the journal Research In the Mathematical Sciences in August 2019.

This bound was further slightly improved in April 2020 by Platt and Trudgian to formula_26.

