<doc id="45270" wikidata="Q3058212" url="?curid=45270" title="Measure space">
<text>A measure space is a basic object of measure theory, a branch of mathematics that studies generalized notions of volumes. It contains an underlying set, the subsets of this set that are feasible for measuring (the -algebra) and the method that is used for measuring (the measure). One important example of a measure space is a probability space.

A measurable space consists of the first two components without a specific measure.

==Definition==

A measure space is a triple formula_1 where
* formula_2 is a set
* formula_3 is a -algebra on the set formula_2
* formula_5 is a measure on formula_6

In other words, a measure space consists of a measurable space formula_6 together with a measure on it.

==Example==

Set formula_8. The formula_9-algebra on finite sets such as the one above is usually the power set, which is the set of all subsets (of a given set) and is denoted by formula_10 Sticking with this convention, we set
formula_11

In this simple case, the power set can be written down explicitly:
formula_12

As the measure, define formula_13 by 
formula_14
so formula_15 (by additivity of measures) and formula_16 (by definition of measures).

This leads to the measure space formula_17 It is a probability space, since formula_18 The measure formula_13 corresponds to the Bernoulli distribution with formula_20 which is for example used to model a fair coin flip.

==Important classes of measure spaces==

Most important classes of measure spaces are defined by the properties of their associated measures. This includes, in order of increasing generality:
* Probability spaces, a measure space where the measure is a probability measure
* Finite measure spaces, where the measure is a finite measure
* formula_21-finite measure spaces, where the measure is a formula_22-finite measure

Another class of measure spaces are the complete measure spaces.

